Hi.

This is an old thread, but Google finds it so I'll contribute.

For JTable, set the default editor:

[geshi lang=Java] 
myJTable.setDefaultEditor(String.class, new NonStupidTableCellEditor());

public class NonStupidTableCellEditor extends javax.swing.AbstractCellEditor implements
		TableCellEditor {
	JTextField component = new JTextField();

	@Override
	public Component getTableCellEditorComponent(JTable table, Object value,
			boolean isSelected, int row, int column) {
			component.setText(value.toString());
			component.setSelectionStart(0);
			component.setSelectionEnd(value.toString().length());
			return component;
	}

	@Override
	public Object getCellEditorValue() {
		return component.getText();
	}
}
[/geshi]

For standard JTextFields (which have the same stupid behaviour), set the caret:

[geshi lang=Java]
myJTextField.setCaret(new NonStupidCaret());

public class NonStupidCaret extends DefaultCaret {
	public void focusGained(FocusEvent e) {
		JTextComponent c;
		c = getComponent();
		if (c.isEnabled()) {
			c.setSelectionStart(0);
			c.setSelectionEnd(c.getText().length());
			setSelectionVisible(true);
			if (c.isEditable()) {
				setVisible(true);
				setBlinkRate(500);
			}
		}
	}
}
[/geshi]

The "setBlinkRate(500)" is a bit dumb, but it occasionally brings the flashing cursor back (and sometimes doesn't).

I used Derek's code, but did it a bit different:

		myTable.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
			@Override
			public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
				int col = myTable.getSelectedColumn();
				TableCellEditor editor = myTable.getColumnModel().getColumn(col).getCellEditor();
				if (editor != null &amp;&amp; editor instanceof MyCellEditor) {
					char c = e.getKeyChar();
					if (Character.isLetterOrDigit(c) || Character.isWhitespace(c)) {
						((MyCellEditor) editor).setIsActivatedByKeyboard(true);
					}
				}
			}
		});

To MyCellEditor I added a field activatedByKeyboard, which purpose is obvious.
MyCellEditor's  method for getting component looks like this:

	@Override
	public Component getTableCellEditorComponent(JTable table, Object value, boolean isSelected, int row, int column) {
		Component editor = super.getTableCellEditorComponent(table, value, isSelected, row, column);
		if (activatedByKeyboard) {
			((NumberField) editor).setText("");
		}
		return editor;
	}

Also I have an AncestorListener attached to the component responsible for edititng cell values, and in that listener I wrote such code:
@Override
													public void ancestorRemoved(AncestorEvent e) {
														TableCellEditor editor = labsTable.getColumnModel().getColumn(1).getCellEditor();
														((NumberFieldCellEditor) editor).setIsActivatedByKeyboard(false);
													}

Now everything works just fine, including cancelling edits by pressing Esc key.

sorry for my poor English and somewhat messy thinking, but I hope I provided enough information anyone to grasp my idea.

